# opt = get_optimizer(...)  # Initialize your optimizer as before

# for epoch in range(num_epochs):
#     for inputs, labels in dataloader:
#         # ... (forward pass, loss calculation, etc.) ...
#         loss.backward()
#         opt.step(closure=opt.gradient_anchor) # Call the anchoring function after stepping.
#         opt.zero_grad()
```
This approach incorporates a form of "soft" regularization and dynamic learning rate adjustment based on layer type. The gradient anchoring helps stabilize training and prevent overfitting, while the adaptable weight decay allows for more nuanced control over the complexity of different parts of the model. Remember that the efficacy of these modifications will depend on the specific task and dataset, so experimentation is key.


